import math
def H(p): return -sum(x*math.log2(x) for x in p if x>0)
def CE(p, q): return -sum(pi*math.log2(qi) for pi, qi in zip(p,q) if pi>0)
def KL(p, q): return sum(pi*math.log2(pi/qi) for pi,qi in zip(p,q) if pi>0)
P=[0.7,0.3]; Q=[0.5,0.5]
print(round(CE(P,Q),4), round(H(P)+KL(P,Q),4))   # equal
```

The identity holds exactly. Since H(P) (the entropy of the *true* labels) is fixed — it doesn't depend on the model — minimizing cross-entropy H(P,Q) over the model's predictions Q is **identical** to minimizing KL(P‖Q), i.e. making the predicted distribution match the true one. That's the theoretical justification for using cross-entropy as the loss in essentially every classifier and language model. Related: **perplexity** = 2^{cross-entropy} is the effective number of equally-likely choices the model is deciding among.
